originalText: ::You see plenty of photos depicting various jet skis and quad bikes, naked and semi-naked women, as well as creative sculptures composed entirely of stacked brew bottles; the rest are pictures of unrelated but amusing things.::

::This folder mostly contains sound recordings of what appear to be live performances of bands playing in Junkyard. The file names do not seem to correspond to band names but rather describe the band's sound: rat-rap, droning bots, derailed yodeling, boring old farts, and scrap metal.::

::You see a grid map of the waterways with many little green dots scattered throughout; the larger green dot is marked as "RSS" and is located at your current position. Some dots are emitting circular pulses whose lines intersect with and paint the map: The terrain may be gray and dull, but the moving shapes are colorful and vibrant and are tagged with quadruple-character codes unfamiliar to you. Other dots lay dormant until something appears in their proximity, at which point some activate and begin emitting pulses just like the rest, whereas the few ones that remain passive display an icon as to signal that something is near them but do not track its exact position.

It is evident that this sonar station is able to track virtually all waterway traffic with exceptional accuracy.::

::[Hacking] Attempt to access and manipulate the settings in order to cause damage to the sonar station.::

::The software you're trying to hack appears to be ancient, even by Biocorp standards. Fortunately, it is just as vulnerable, if not more, to advanced contemporary hacking techniques. After unlocking the settings, you go to power section with the intent of overloading and burning critical components through setting manipulation. ::

::The sonar is equipped with numerous safety measures designed to prevent just that, but with some skill you manage to circumvent those, at least the software ones. That proves to be sufficient, though, and soon enough you manage to manipulate the settings in such a way as to systematically fry all the major components as well as the sonar's power core.

The sonar's lights go dark, and a faint smell of burned electronics reaches your nose.::
